# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: data-engineering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] Kafka was originally developed at LinkedIn, and was subsequently open sourced in early 2011.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] Jay Kreps, Neha Narkhede and Jun Rao helped co-create Kafka.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] Graduation from the Apache Incubator occurred on 23 October 2012.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] Jay Kreps chose to name the software after the author Franz Kafka because it is "a system optimized for writing", and he liked Kafka's work.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] Apache Kafka is a distributed log-based messaging system that guarantees ordering within individual partitions rather than across the entire topic.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] Unlike queue-based systems, Kafka retains messages in a durable, append-only log, allowing multiple consumers to read at different offsets.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] Kafka uses manual offset management, giving consumers control over retries and failure handling.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] If a consumer fails to process a message, it can delay committing the offset, preventing further progress in that partition while other partitions remain unaffected.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] This partition-based design enables fault isolation and parallel processing while allowing ordering to be maintained within partitions, depending on consumer handling.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] In 2025, Apache Kafka introduced "Queues for Kafka", adding share groups as an alternative to consumer groups.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] This feature enables queue-like semantics where consumers can cooperatively process records from the same partitions, with individual message acknowledgment and delivery tracking.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] Unlike traditional consumer groups where partitions are exclusively assigned, share groups allow the number of consumers to exceed partition count, making it ideal for work-queue patterns while maintaining Kafka's durability and scalability benefits.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] This development addresses the common challenge of "over-partitioning" that many Kafka users face.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] Kafka Connect (or Connect API) is a framework to import/export data from/to other systems.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] It was added in the Kafka 0.9.0.0 release and uses the Producer and Consumer API internally.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] The Connect framework itself executes so-called "connectors" that implement the actual logic to read/write data from other systems.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] Kafka Streams (or Streams API) is a stream-processing library written in Java.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] It was added in the Kafka 0.10.0.0 release.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] The library allows for the development of stateful stream-processing applications that are scalable, elastic, and fully fault-tolerant.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] The main API is a stream-processing domain-specific language (DSL) that offers high-level operators like filter, map, grouping, windowing, aggregation, joins, and the notion of tables.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] Additionally, the Processor API can be used to implement custom operators for a more low-level development approach.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] The DSL and Processor API can be mixed, too.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] For stateful stream processing, Kafka Streams uses RocksDB to maintain local operator state.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] Because RocksDB can write to disk, the maintained state can be larger than available main memory.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] For fault-tolerance, all updates to local state stores are also written into a topic in the Kafka cluster.
[src:data-engineering/apache-kafka] This allows recreating state by reading those topics and feed all data into RocksDB.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] In computing, **batch processing** is the running of a software job in an automated and unattended way.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] A user schedules a job to run and then waits for a processing system to run it.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Typically, a job is scheduled to run at a configured time of day or when an event occurs or when computer resources are available.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] The term "batch processing" originates in the traditional classification of methods of production as job production (one-off production), batch production (production of a "batch" of multiple items at once, one stage at a time), and flow production (mass production, all stages in process at once).
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Early computers were capable of running only one program at a time.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Each user had sole control of the machine for a scheduled period of time.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] They would arrive at the computer with program and data, often on punched paper cards and magnetic or paper tape, and would load their program, run and debug it, and carry off their output when done.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] As computers became faster the setup and takedown time became a larger percentage of available computer time.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Programs called *monitors*, the forerunners of operating systems, were developed which could process a series, or "batch", of programs, often from magnetic tape prepared offline.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] The monitor would be loaded into the computer and run the first job of the batch.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] At the end of the job it would regain control and load and run the next until the batch was complete.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Often the output of the batch would be written to magnetic tape and printed or punched offline.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Examples of monitors were IBM's *Fortran Monitor System*, SOS (Share Operating System), and finally IBSYS for IBM's 709x systems in 1960.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Third-generation computers capable of multiprogramming began to appear in the 1960s.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Instead of running one batch job at a time, these systems can have multiple batch programs running at the same time in order to keep the system as busy as possible.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] One or more programs might be awaiting input, one actively running on the CPU, and others generating output.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Instead of offline input and output, programs called spoolers read jobs from cards, disk, or remote terminals and place them in a job queue to be run.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] In order to prevent deadlocks the job scheduler needs to know each job's resource requirements—memory, magnetic tapes, mountable disks, etc., so various scripting languages were developed to supply this information in a structured way.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Probably the most well-known is IBM's *Job Control Language* (JCL).
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Job schedulers select jobs to run according to a variety of criteria, including priority, memory size, etc.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Remote batch is a procedure for submitting batch jobs from remote terminals, often equipped with a punch card reader and a line printer.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Sometimes asymmetric multiprocessing is used to spool batch input and output for one or more large computers using an attached smaller and less-expensive system, as in the IBM System/360 Attached Support Processor.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] The first general-purpose time-sharing system, Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS), was compatible with batch processing.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] This facilitated transitioning from batch processing to interactive computing.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] From the late 1960s onwards, interactive computing such as via text-based computer terminal interfaces (as in Unix shells or read-eval-print loops), and later graphical user interfaces became common.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Non-interactive computation, both one-off jobs such as compilation, and processing of multiple items in batches, became retrospectively referred to as *batch processing*, and the term *batch job* (in early use often "batch *of* jobs") became common.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Early use is particularly found at the University of Michigan, around the Michigan Terminal System (MTS).
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Although timesharing did exist, its use was not robust enough for corporate data processing; none of this was related to the earlier unit record equipment, which was human-operated.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Non-interactive computation remains widespread in computing, both for general data processing and for system "housekeeping" tasks (using system software).
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] A high-level program (executing multiple programs, with some additional "glue" logic) is today most often called a *script*, and written in scripting languages, particularly shell scripts for system tasks; in IBM PC DOS and MS-DOS this is instead known as a batch file.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] That includes UNIX-based computers, Microsoft Windows, macOS (whose foundation is the BSD Unix kernel), and even smartphones.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] A running script, particularly one executed from an interactive login session, is often known as a job, but that term is used very ambiguously.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] "There is no direct counterpart to z/OS batch processing in PC or UNIX systems.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Batch jobs are typically executed at a scheduled time or on an as-needed basis.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Batch applications are still critical in most organizations in large part because many common business processes are amenable to batch processing.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] While online systems can also function when manual intervention is not desired, they are not typically optimized to perform high-volume, repetitive tasks.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Therefore, even new systems usually contain one or more batch applications for updating information at the end of the day, generating reports, printing documents, and other non-interactive tasks that must complete reliably within certain business deadlines.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Some applications are amenable to flow processing, namely those that only need data from a single input at once (not totals, for instance): start the next step for each input as it completes the previous step.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] In this case flow processing lowers latency for individual inputs, allowing them to be completed without waiting for the entire batch to finish.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] However, many applications require data from all records, notably computations such as totals.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] In this case the entire batch must be completed before one has a usable result: partial results are not usable.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Modern batch applications make use of modern batch frameworks such as Jem The Bee, Spring Batch or implementations of JSR 352 written for Java, and other frameworks for other programming languages, to provide the fault tolerance and scalability required for high-volume processing.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] In order to ensure high-speed processing, batch applications are often integrated with grid computing solutions to partition a batch job over a large number of processors, although there are significant programming challenges in doing so.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] High volume batch processing places particularly heavy demands on system and application architectures as well.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Architectures that feature strong input/output performance and vertical scalability, including modern mainframe computers, tend to provide better batch performance than alternatives.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Scripting languages became popular as they evolved along with batch processing.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] A *batch window* is "a period of less-intensive online activity", when the computer system is able to run batch jobs without interference from, or with, interactive online systems.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] A bank's *end-of-day (EOD)* jobs require the concept of *cutover*, where transaction and data are cut off for a particular day's batch activity ("deposits after 3 PM will be processed the next day").
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] As requirements for online systems uptime expanded to support globalization, the Internet, and other business needs, the batch window shrank and increasing emphasis was placed on techniques that would require online data to be available for a maximum amount of time.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] The *batch size* refers to the number of work units to be processed within one batch operation.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] The IBM mainframe z/OS operating system or platform has arguably the most highly refined and evolved set of batch processing facilities owing to its origins, long history, and continuing evolution.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Today such systems commonly support hundreds or even thousands of concurrent online and batch tasks within a single operating system image.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] The Unix programs `cron`, `at`, and `batch` (today `batch` is a variant of `at`) allow for complex scheduling of jobs.
[src:data-engineering/batch-processing] Most high-performance computing clusters use batch processing to maximize cluster usage.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] In databases, **change data capture** (**CDC**) is a set of software design patterns used to determine and track the data that has changed (the "deltas") so that action can be taken using the changed data.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] The result is a **delta-driven dataset**.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] CDC is an approach to data integration that is based on the identification, capture and delivery of the changes made to enterprise data sources.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] For instance it can be used for incremental update of data loading.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] CDC occurs often in data warehouse environments since capturing and preserving the state of data across time is one of the core functions of a data warehouse, but CDC can be utilized in any database or data repository system.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] System developers can set up CDC mechanisms in a number of ways and in any one or a combination of system layers from application logic down to physical storage.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] In a simplified CDC context, one computer system has data believed to have changed from a previous point in time, and a second computer system needs to take action based on that changed data.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] The former is the source, the latter is the target.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] It is possible that the source and target are the same system physically, but that would not change the design pattern logically.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] Multiple CDC solutions can exist in a single system.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] Tables whose changes must be captured may have a column that represents the time of **last** change.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] Names such as LAST_UPDATE, LAST_MODIFIED, etc. are common.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] Any row in any table that has a timestamp in that column that is more recent than the last time data was captured is considered to have changed.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] Timestamps on rows are also frequently used for optimistic locking so this column is often available.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] Database designers give tables whose changes must be captured a column that contains a version number.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] Names such as VERSION_NUMBER, etc. are common.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] One technique is to mark each changed row with a version number.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] A current version is maintained for the table, or possibly a group of tables.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] This is stored in a supporting construct such as a reference table.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] When a change capture occurs, all data with the latest version number is considered to have changed.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] Once the change capture is complete, the reference table is updated with a new version number.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] (Do not confuse this technique with row-level versioning used for optimistic locking.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] For optimistic locking each row has an independent version number, typically a sequential counter.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] This allows a process to atomically update a row and increment its counter only if another process has not incremented the counter.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] But CDC cannot use row-level versions to find all changes unless it knows the original "starting" version of every row.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] This technique can either supplement or complement timestamps and versioning.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] It can configure an alternative if, for example, a status column is set up on a table row indicating that the row has changed (e.g., a boolean column that, when set to true, indicates that the row has changed).
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] Otherwise, it can act as a complement to the previous methods, indicating that a row, despite having a new version number or a later date, still shouldn't be updated on the target (for example, the data may require human validation).
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] This approach combines the three previously discussed methods.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] As noted, it is not uncommon to see multiple CDC solutions at work in a single system, however, the combination of time, version, and status provides a particularly powerful mechanism and programmers should utilize them as a trio where possible.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] The three elements are not redundant or superfluous.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] May include a publish/subscribe pattern to communicate the changed data to multiple targets.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] In this approach, triggers log events that happen to the transactional table into another queue table that can later be "played back".
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] For example, imagine an Accounts table, when transactions are taken against this table, triggers would fire that would then store a history of the event or even the deltas into a separate queue table.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] The queue table might have schema with the following fields: Id, TableName, RowId, Timestamp, Operation.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] The data inserted for our Account sample might be: 1, Accounts, 76, 2008-11-02 00:15, Update.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] More complicated designs might log the actual data that changed.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] This queue table could then be "played back" to replicate the data from the source system to a target.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] Data capture offers a challenge in that the structure, contents and use of a transaction log is specific to a database management system.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] Unlike data access, no standard exists for transaction logs.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] Most database management systems do not document the internal format of their transaction logs, although some provide programmatic interfaces to their transaction logs (for example: Oracle, DB2, SQL/MP, SQL/MX and SQL Server 2008).
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] As often occurs in complex domains, the final solution to a CDC problem may have to balance many competing concerns.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] Change data capture both increases in complexity and reduces in value if the source system saves metadata changes when the data itself is not modified.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] For example, some Data models track the user who last looked at but did not change the data in the same structure as the data.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] This results in noise in the Change Data Capture.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] Actually tracking the changes depends on the data source.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] If the data is being persisted in a modern database then Change Data Capture is a simple matter of permissions.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] If the data is not in a modern database, CDC becomes a programming challenge.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] Sometimes the slowly changing dimension is used as an alternative method.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] CDC and SCD are similar in that both methods can detect changes in a data set.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] The most common forms of SCD are type 1 (overwrite), type 2 (maintain history) or 3 (only previous and current value).
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] SCD 2 can be useful if history is needed in the target system.
[src:data-engineering/change-data-capture] CDC overwrites in the target system (akin to SCD1), and is ideal when only the changed data needs to arrive at the target, i.e. a *delta-driven dataset*.
[src:data-engineering/data-lake] A **data lake** is a system or repository of data stored in its natural, raw format, usually object blobs or files.
[src:data-engineering/data-lake] A data lake is usually a single store of data including raw copies of source system data, sensor data, social data etc., and transformed data used for tasks such as reporting, visualization, advanced analytics, and machine learning.
[src:data-engineering/data-lake] A data lake can include structured data from relational databases (rows and columns), semi-structured data (CSV, logs, XML, JSON), unstructured data (emails, documents, PDFs), and binary data (images, audio, video).
[src:data-engineering/data-lake] A data lake can be established *on premises* (within an organization's data centers) or *in the cloud* (using cloud services).
[src:data-engineering/data-lake] James Dixon, then chief technology officer at Pentaho, coined the term by 2011 to contrast it with data mart, which is a smaller repository of interesting attributes derived from raw data.
[src:data-engineering/data-lake] In promoting data lakes, he argued that data marts have several inherent problems, such as information siloing.
[src:data-engineering/data-lake] PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) said that data lakes could "put an end to data silos".
[src:data-engineering/data-lake] Many companies use cloud storage services such as Google Cloud Storage and Amazon S3 or a distributed file system such as Apache Hadoop distributed file system (HDFS).
[src:data-engineering/data-lake] There is a gradual academic interest in the concept of data lakes.
[src:data-engineering/data-lake] For example, Personal DataLake at Cardiff University is a new type of data lake which aims at managing big data of individual users by providing a single point of collecting, organizing, and sharing personal data.
[src:data-engineering/data-lake] Early data lakes, such as Hadoop 1.0, had limited capabilities because it only supported batch-oriented processing (Map Reduce).
[src:data-engineering/data-lake] Interacting with it required expertise in Java, map reduce and higher-level tools like Apache Pig, Apache Spark and Apache Hive (which were also originally batch-oriented).
[src:data-engineering/data-lake] Poorly managed data lakes have been facetiously called data swamps.
[src:data-engineering/data-lake] In June 2015, David Needle characterized "so-called data lakes" as "one of the more controversial ways to manage big data".
[src:data-engineering/data-lake] PwC was also careful to note in their research that not all data lake initiatives are successful.
[src:data-engineering/data-lake] They describe companies that build successful data lakes as gradually maturing their lake as they figure out which data and metadata are important to the organization.
[src:data-engineering/data-lake] Another criticism is that the term *data lake* is used with many different meanings.
[src:data-engineering/data-lake] It may be used to refer to, for example: any tools or data management practices that are not data warehouses; a particular technology for implementation; a raw data reservoir; a hub for ETL offload; or a central hub for self-service analytics.
[src:data-engineering/data-lake] While critiques of data lakes are warranted, in many cases they apply to other data projects as well.
[src:data-engineering/data-lake] For example, the definition of *data warehouse* is also changeable, and not all data warehouse efforts have been successful.
[src:data-engineering/data-lake] In response to various critiques, McKinsey noted that the data lake should be viewed as a service model for delivering business value within the enterprise, not a technology outcome.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] In computing, a **data warehouse** (**DW** or **DWH**), also known as an **enterprise data warehouse** (**EDW**), is a system used for reporting and data analysis and is a core component of business intelligence.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are central repositories of data integrated from disparate sources.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] They store current and historical data organized in a way that is optimized for data analysis, generation of reports, and developing insights across the integrated data.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] They are intended to be used by analysts and managers to help make organizational decisions.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The data stored in the warehouse is uploaded from operational systems (such as marketing or sales).
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The data may pass through an operational data store and may require data cleansing for additional operations to ensure data quality before it is used in the data warehouse for reporting.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The two main workflows for building a data warehouse system are extract, transform, load (ETL) and extract, load, transform (ELT).
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Operational databases are optimized for the preservation of data integrity and speed of recording of business transactions through use of database normalization and an entity–relationship model.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Operational system designers generally follow database normalization to ensure data integrity.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Fully normalized database designs often result in information from a business transaction being stored in dozens to hundreds of tables.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Relational databases are efficient at managing the relationships between these tables.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The databases have very fast insert/update performance because only a small amount of data in those tables is affected by each transaction.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] To improve performance, older data are periodically purged.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are optimized for analytic access patterns, which usually involve selecting specific fields rather than all fields as is common in operational databases.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Because of these differences in access, operational databases (loosely, OLTP) benefit from the use of a row-oriented database management system (DBMS), whereas analytics databases (loosely, OLAP) benefit from the use of a column-oriented DBMS.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Operational systems maintain a snapshot of the business, while warehouses maintain historic data through ETL processes that periodically migrate data from the operational systems to the warehouse.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Online analytical processing (OLAP) is characterized by a low rate of transactions and complex queries that involve aggregations.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Response time is an effective performance measure of OLAP systems.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] OLAP applications are widely used for data mining.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] OLAP databases store aggregated, historical data in multi-dimensional schemas (usually star schemas).
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] OLAP systems typically have a data latency of a few hours, while data mart latency is closer to one day.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The OLAP approach is used to analyze multidimensional data from multiple sources and perspectives.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The three basic operations in OLAP are roll-up (consolidation), drill-down, and slicing & dicing.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Online transaction processing (OLTP) is characterized by a large numbers of short online transactions (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE).
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] OLTP systems emphasize fast query processing and maintaining data integrity in multi-access environments.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] For OLTP systems, performance is the number of transactions per second.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] OLTP databases contain detailed and current data.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The schema used to store transactional databases is the entity model (usually 3NF).
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Normalization is the norm for data modeling techniques in this system.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Predictive analytics is about finding and quantifying hidden patterns in the data using complex mathematical models to prepare for different future outcomes, including demand for products, and make better decisions.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] By contrast, OLAP focuses on historical data analysis and is reactive.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Predictive systems are also used for customer relationship management (CRM).
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] A Database is an organized collection of data that is stored and managed electronically.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] It is designed to store, retrieve and manage structured data using a DBMS(Database Management Software) for querying and manipulating the data.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] A data mart is a simple data warehouse focused on a single subject or functional area.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Hence it draws data from a limited number of sources such as sales, finance or marketing.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Data marts are often built and controlled by a single department in an organization.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The sources could be internal operational systems, a central data warehouse, or external data.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Types of data marts include dependent, independent, and hybrid data marts.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] A Data lake is a centralized repository that stores large volume of data in raw format that is processed at the run time.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] It can collect data from multiple sources such as APIs, Files, databases, sensors, websites, etc.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Unlike data warehouses, data lakes stores data is structured, semi-structured and unstructured format that makes them usable for machine learning and big data processing.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The typical extract, transform, load (ETL)-based data warehouse uses staging, data integration, and access layers to house its key functions.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The staging layer or staging database stores raw data extracted from each of the disparate source data systems.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The integration layer integrates disparate data sets by transforming the data from the staging layer, often storing this transformed data in an operational data store (ODS) database.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The integrated data are then moved to yet another database, often called the data warehouse database, where the data is arranged into hierarchical groups, often called dimensions, and into facts and aggregate facts.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The combination of facts and dimensions is sometimes called a star schema.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The access layer helps users retrieve data.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The main source of the data is cleansed, transformed, catalogued, and made available for use by managers and other business professionals for data mining, online analytical processing, market research and decision support.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] However, the means to retrieve and analyze data, to extract, transform, and load data, and to manage the data dictionary are also considered essential components of a data warehousing system.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Many references to data warehousing use this broader context.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Thus, an expanded definition of data warehousing includes business intelligence tools, tools to extract, transform, and load data into the repository, and tools to manage and retrieve metadata.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] ELT-based data warehousing gets rid of a separate ETL tool for data transformation.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Instead, it maintains a staging area inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] In this approach, data gets extracted from heterogeneous source systems and are then directly loaded into the data warehouse, before any transformation occurs.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] All necessary transformations are then handled inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Finally, the manipulated data gets loaded into target tables in the same data warehouse.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] A data warehouse maintains a copy of information from the source transaction systems.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The concept of data warehousing dates back to the late 1980s when IBM researchers Barry Devlin and Paul Murphy developed the "business data warehouse".
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] In essence, the data warehousing concept was intended to provide an architectural model for the flow of data from operational systems to decision support environments.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The concept attempted to address the various problems associated with this flow, mainly the high costs associated with it.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] In the absence of a data warehousing architecture, an enormous amount of redundancy was required to support multiple decision support environments.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] In larger corporations, it was typical for multiple decision support environments to operate independently.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Though each environment served different users, they often required much of the same stored data.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The process of gathering, cleaning and integrating data from various sources, usually from long-term existing operational systems (usually referred to as legacy systems), was typically in part replicated for each environment.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Moreover, the operational systems were frequently reexamined as new decision support requirements emerged.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Often new requirements necessitated gathering, cleaning and integrating new data from "data marts" that was tailored for ready access by users.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Additionally, with the publication of The IRM Imperative (Wiley & Sons, 1991) by James M.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Kerr, the idea of managing and putting a dollar value on an organization's data resources and then reporting that value as an asset on a balance sheet became popular.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] In the book, Kerr described a way to populate subject-area databases from data derived from transaction-driven systems to create a storage area where summary data could be further leveraged to inform executive decision-making.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] This concept served to promote further thinking of how a data warehouse could be developed and managed in a practical way within any enterprise.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] A fact is a value or measurement in the system being managed.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Raw facts are ones reported by the reporting entity.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Raw facts are aggregated to higher levels in various dimensions to extract information more relevant to the service or business.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] These are called aggregated facts or summaries.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] For example, if there are three BTSs in a city, then the facts above can be aggregated to the city level in the network dimension.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The two most important approaches to store data in a warehouse are dimensional and normalized.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The dimensional approach uses a star schema as proposed by Ralph Kimball.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The normalized approach, also called the third normal form (3NF) is an entity-relational normalized model proposed by Bill Inmon.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] In a dimensional approach, transaction data is partitioned into "facts", which are usually numeric transaction data, and "dimensions", which are the reference information that gives context to the facts.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] This dimensional approach makes data easier to understand and speeds up data retrieval.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Dimensional structures are easy for business users to understand because the structure is divided into measurements/facts and context/dimensions.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Facts are related to the organization's business processes and operational system, and dimensions are the context about them (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Another advantage is that the dimensional model does not involve a relational database every time.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Thus, this type of modeling technique is very useful for end-user queries in data warehouse.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The model of facts and dimensions can also be understood as a data cube, where dimensions are the categorical coordinates in a multi-dimensional cube, the fact is a value corresponding to the coordinates.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] It is difficult to modify the warehouse structure if the organization changes the way it does business.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] In the normalized approach, the data in the warehouse are stored following, to a degree, database normalization rules.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Normalized relational database tables are grouped into *subject areas* (for example, customers, products and finance).
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] When used in large enterprises, the result is dozens of tables linked by a web of joins.(Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The main advantage of this approach is that it is straightforward to add information into the database.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Disadvantages include that, because of the large number of tables, it can be difficult for users to join data from different sources into meaningful information and access the information without a precise understanding of the date sources and the data structure of the data warehouse.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Both normalized and dimensional models can be represented in entity–relationship diagrams because both contain joined relational tables.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The difference between them is the degree of normalization.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] These approaches are not mutually exclusive, and there are other approaches.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Dimensional approaches can involve normalizing data to a degree (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] In *Information-Driven Business*, Robert Hillard compares the two approaches based on the information needs of the business problem.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] He concludes that normalized models hold far more information than their dimensional equivalents (even when the same fields are used in both models) but at the cost of usability.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The technique measures information quantity in terms of information entropy and usability in terms of the Small Worlds data transformation measure.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] In the *bottom-up* approach, data marts are first created to provide reporting and analytical capabilities for specific business processes.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] These data marts can then be integrated to create a comprehensive data warehouse.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The data warehouse bus architecture is primarily an implementation of "the bus", a collection of confirmed dimensions and confirmed facts, which are dimensions that are shared (in a specific way) between facts in two or more data marts.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The *top-down* approach is designed using a normalized enterprise data model.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] "Atomic" data, that is, data at the greatest level of detail, are stored in the data warehouse.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Dimensional data marts containing data needed for specific business processes or specific departments are created from the data warehouse.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Data warehouses often use a spoke–hub distribution paradigm.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Legacy systems feeding the warehouse often include customer relationship management and enterprise resource planning, generating large amounts of data.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] To consolidate these various data models and facilitate the extract transform load process, data warehouses often make use of an operational data store, the information from which is parsed into the actual data warehouse.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] To reduce data redundancy, larger systems often store the data in a normalized way.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Data marts for specific reports can then be built on top of the data warehouse.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] A hybrid (also called ensemble) data warehouse database is kept on third normal form to eliminate data redundancy.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] A normal relational database, however, is not efficient for business intelligence reports where dimensional modelling is prevalent.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Small data marts can shop for data from the consolidated warehouse and use the filtered, specific data for the fact tables and dimensions required.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The data warehouse provides a single source of information from which the data marts can read, providing a wide range of business information.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The hybrid architecture allows a data warehouse to be replaced with a master data management repository where operational (not static) information could reside.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The data vault modeling components follow hub and spokes architecture.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] This modeling style is a hybrid design, consisting of the best practices from both third normal form and star schema.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The data vault model is not a true third normal form, and breaks some of its rules, but it is a top-down architecture with a bottom up design.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The data vault model is geared to be strictly a data warehouse.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] It is not geared to be end-user accessible, which, when built, still requires the use of a data mart or star schema-based release area for business purposes.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] There are basic features that define the data in the data warehouse that include subject orientation, data integration, time-variant, nonvolatile data, and data granularity.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Unlike the operational systems, the data in the data warehouse revolves around the subjects of the enterprise.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Subject orientation is not database normalization.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Subject orientation can be really useful for decision-making.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Gathering the required objects is called subject-oriented.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The data found within the data warehouse is integrated.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Since it comes from several operational systems, all inconsistencies must be removed.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Consistencies include naming conventions, measurement of variables, encoding structures, physical attributes of data, and so forth.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] While operational systems reflect current values as they support day-to-day operations, data warehouse data represents a long time horizon (up to 10 years) which means it stores mostly historical data.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] It is mainly meant for data mining and forecasting.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The data in the data warehouse is read-only, which means it cannot be updated, created, or deleted (unless there is a regulatory or statutory obligation to do so).
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] In the data warehouse process, data can be aggregated in data marts at different levels of abstraction.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The user may start looking at the total sale units of a product in an entire region.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Then the user looks at the states in that region.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Finally, they may examine the individual stores in a certain state.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Therefore, typically, the analysis starts at a higher level and drills down to lower levels of details.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] With data virtualization, the data used remains in its original locations and real-time access is established to allow analytics across multiple sources creating a virtual data warehouse.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] This can aid in resolving some technical difficulties such as compatibility problems when combining data from various platforms, lowering the risk of error caused by faulty data, and guaranteeing that the newest data is used.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Furthermore, avoiding the creation of a new database containing personal information can make it easier to comply with privacy regulations.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] However, with data virtualization, the connection to all necessary data sources must be operational as there is no local copy of the data, which is one of the main drawbacks of the approach.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The different methods used to construct/organize a data warehouse specified by an organization are numerous.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] The hardware utilized, software created and data resources specifically required for the correct functionality of a data warehouse are the main components of the data warehouse architecture.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] All data warehouses have multiple phases in which the requirements of the organization are modified and fine-tuned.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Data warehouses in this stage of evolution are updated on a regular time cycle (usually daily, weekly or monthly) from the operational systems and the data is stored in an integrated reporting-oriented database.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] Data warehouses at this stage are updated from data in the operational systems on a regular basis and the data warehouse data are stored in a data structure designed to facilitate reporting.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] These data warehouses assemble data from different areas of business, so users can look up the information they need across other systems.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] In the healthcare sector, data warehouses are critical components of health informatics, enabling the integration, storage, and analysis of large volumes of clinical, administrative, and operational data.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] These systems consolidate information from disparate sources such as electronic health records (EHRs), laboratory information systems, picture archiving and communication systems (PACS), and medical billing platforms.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] By centralizing data, healthcare data warehouses support a range of functions including population health, clinical decision support, quality improvement, public health surveillance, and medical research.
[src:data-engineering/data-warehouse] These warehouses enable data-driven healthcare by supporting retrospective studies, comparative effectiveness research, and predictive analytics, often with the use of healthcare-applied artificial intelligence.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] A properly designed ETL system extracts data from source systems and enforces data type and data validity standards and ensures it conforms structurally to the requirements of the output.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Some ETL systems can also deliver data in a presentation-ready format so that application developers can build applications and end users can make decisions.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] The ETL process is often used in data warehousing.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] ETL systems commonly integrate data from multiple applications (systems), typically developed and supported by different vendors or hosted on separate computer hardware.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] The separate systems containing the original data are frequently managed and operated by different stakeholders.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] For example, a cost accounting system may combine data from payroll, sales, and purchasing.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] ETL and its variant ELT (extract, load, transform), are increasingly used in cloud-based data warehousing.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Applications involve not only batch processing, but also real-time streaming.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] ETL processing involves extracting the data from the source system(s).
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] In many cases, this represents the most important aspect of ETL, since extracting data correctly sets the stage for the success of subsequent processes.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Most data-warehousing projects combine data from different source systems.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Each separate system may also use a different data organization and/or format.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] The streaming of the extracted data source and loading on-the-fly to the destination database is another way of performing ETL when no intermediate data storage is required.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] An intrinsic part of the extraction involves data validation to confirm whether the data pulled from the sources has the correct/expected values in a given domain (such as a pattern/default or list of values).
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] If the data fails the validation rules, it is rejected entirely or in part.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] The rejected data is ideally reported back to the source system for further analysis to identify and to rectify incorrect records or perform data wrangling.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] In the data transformation stage, a series of rules or functions are applied to the extracted data in order to prepare it for loading into the end target.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] An important function of transformation is data cleansing, which aims to pass only "proper" data to the target.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] The challenge when different systems interact is in the relevant systems' interfacing and communicating.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Character sets that may be available in one system may not be in others.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] The load phase loads the data into the end target, which can be any data store including a simple delimited flat file or a data warehouse.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Depending on the requirements of the organization, this process varies widely.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Some data warehouses may overwrite existing information with cumulative information; updating extracted data is frequently done on a daily, weekly, or monthly basis.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Other data warehouses (or even other parts of the same data warehouse) may add new data in a historical form at regular intervals – for example, hourly.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] To understand this, consider a data warehouse that is required to maintain sales records of the last year.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] This data warehouse overwrites any data older than a year with newer data.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] However, the entry of data for any one year window is made in a historical manner.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] The timing and scope to replace or append are strategic design choices dependent on the time available and the business needs.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] More complex systems can maintain a history and audit trail of all changes to the data loaded in the data warehouse.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] As the load phase interacts with a database, the constraints defined in the database schema – as well as in triggers activated upon data load – apply (for example, uniqueness, referential integrity, mandatory fields), which also contribute to the overall data quality performance of the ETL process.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Audit reports (for example, on compliance with business rules.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Archive (Extreme, space-efficient compression for very rarely used, old data.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] ETL processes can involve considerable complexity, and significant operational problems can occur with improperly designed ETL systems.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] The range of data values or data quality in an operational system may exceed the expectations of designers at the time validation and transformation rules are specified.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Data profiling of a source during data analysis can identify the data conditions that must be managed by transform rules specifications, leading to an amendment of validation rules explicitly and implicitly implemented in the ETL process.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Data warehouses are typically assembled from a variety of data sources with different formats and purposes.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] As such, ETL is a key process to bring all the data together in a standard, homogeneous environment.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Design analysis should establish the scalability of an ETL system across the lifetime of its usage – including understanding the volumes of data that must be processed within service level agreements.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] The time available to extract from source systems may change, which may mean the same amount of data may have to be processed in less time.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Some ETL systems have to scale to process terabytes of data to update data warehouses with tens of terabytes of data.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Increasing volumes of data may require designs that can scale from daily batch to multiple-day micro batch to integration with message queues or real-time change-data-capture for continuous transformation and update.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Unique keys play an important part in all relational databases, as they tie everything together.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] A unique key is a column that identifies a given entity, whereas a foreign key is a column in another table that refers to a primary key.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Keys can comprise several columns, in which case they are composite keys.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] In many cases, the primary key is an auto-generated integer that has no meaning for the business entity being represented, but solely exists for the purpose of the relational database – commonly referred to as a surrogate key.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] As there is usually more than one data source getting loaded into the warehouse, the keys are an important concern to be addressed.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] For example: customers might be represented in several data sources, with their Social Security number as the primary key in one source, their phone number in another, and a surrogate in the third.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Yet a data warehouse may require the consolidation of all the customer information into one dimension.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] A recommended way to deal with the concern involves adding a warehouse surrogate key, which is used as a foreign key from the fact table.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Usually, updates occur to a dimension's source data, which must be reflected in the data warehouse.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] If the primary key of the source data is required for reporting, the dimension already contains that piece of information for each row.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] If the source data uses a surrogate key, the warehouse must keep track of it even though it is never used in queries or reports; it is done by creating a lookup table that contains the warehouse surrogate key and the originating key.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] This way, the dimension is not polluted with surrogates from various source systems, while the ability to update is preserved.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] The lookup table is used in different ways depending on the nature of the source data.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] A new dimension row is added with the new state of the source system, while the previous dimension row is updated to reflect it is no longer active and time of deactivation.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] ETL vendors benchmark their record-systems at multiple TB (terabytes) per hour (or ~1 GB per second) using powerful servers with multiple CPUs, multiple hard drives, multiple gigabit-network connections, and much memory.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] In real life, the slowest part of an ETL process usually occurs in the database load phase.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Databases may perform slowly because they have to take care of concurrency, integrity maintenance, and indices.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Still, even using bulk operations, database access is usually the bottleneck in the ETL process.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Whether to do certain operations in the database or outside may involve a trade-off.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] For example, removing duplicates using `distinct` may be slow in the database; thus, it makes sense to do it outside.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] On the other side, if using `distinct` significantly (x100) decreases the number of rows to be extracted, then it makes sense to remove duplications as early as possible in the database before unloading data.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] A common source of problems in ETL is a big number of dependencies among ETL jobs.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] For example, job "B" cannot start while job "A" is not finished.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] One can usually achieve better performance by visualizing all processes on a graph, and trying to reduce the graph making maximum use of parallelism, and making "chains" of consecutive processing as short as possible.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Again, partitioning of big tables and their indices can really help.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Another common issue occurs when the data are spread among several databases, and processing is done in those databases sequentially.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Sometimes database replication may be involved as a method of copying data between databases – it can significantly slow down the whole process.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] This approach allows processing to take maximum advantage of parallelism.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] For example, if you need to load data into two databases, you can run the loads in parallel (instead of loading into the first – and then replicating into the second).
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Sometimes processing must take place sequentially.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] For example, dimensional (reference) data are needed before one can get and validate the rows for main "fact" tables.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Some ETL software implementations include parallel processing.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] This enables a number of methods to improve overall performance of ETL when dealing with large volumes of data.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] All three types of parallelism usually operate combined in a single job or task.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] An additional difficulty comes with making sure that the data being uploaded is relatively consistent.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Because multiple source databases may have different update cycles (some may be updated every few minutes, while others may take days or weeks), an ETL system may be required to hold back certain data until all sources are synchronized.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Likewise, where a warehouse may have to be reconciled to the contents in a source system or with the general ledger, establishing synchronization and reconciliation points becomes necessary.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Data warehousing procedures usually subdivide a big ETL process into smaller pieces running sequentially or in parallel.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] To keep track of data flows, it makes sense to tag each data row with "row_id", and tag each piece of the process with "run_id".
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] In case of a failure, having these IDs help to roll back and rerun the failed piece.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Best practice also calls for *checkpoints*, which are states when certain phases of the process are completed.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Once at a checkpoint, it is a good idea to write everything to disk, clean out some temporary files, log the state, etc.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] An established ETL framework may improve connectivity and scalability.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] A good ETL tool must be able to communicate with the many different relational databases and read the various file formats used throughout an organization.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] ETL tools have started to migrate into enterprise application integration, or even enterprise service bus, systems that now cover much more than just the extraction, transformation, and loading of data.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Many ETL vendors now have data profiling, data quality, and metadata capabilities.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] A common use case for ETL tools include converting CSV files to formats readable by relational databases.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] A typical translation of millions of records is facilitated by ETL tools that enable users to input CSV-like data feeds/files and import them into a database with as little code as possible.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] ETL tools are typically used by a broad range of professionals – from students in computer science looking to quickly import large data sets to database architects in charge of company account management, ETL tools have become a convenient tool that can be relied on to get maximum performance.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] ETL tools in most cases contain a GUI that helps users conveniently transform data, using a visual data mapper, as opposed to writing large programs to parse files and modify data types.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] While ETL tools have traditionally been for developers and IT staff, research firm Gartner wrote that the new trend is to provide these capabilities to business users so they can themselves create connections and data integrations when needed, rather than going to the IT staff.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Gartner refers to these non-technical users as Citizen Integrators.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] In online transaction processing (OLTP) applications, changes from individual OLTP instances are detected and logged into a snapshot, or batch, of updates.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] An ETL instance can be used to periodically collect all of these batches, transform them into a common format, and load them into a data lake or warehouse.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Data virtualization can be used to advance ETL processing.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] The application of data virtualization to ETL allowed solving the most common ETL tasks of data migration and application integration for multiple dispersed data sources.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Virtual ETL operates with the abstracted representation of the objects or entities gathered from the variety of relational, semi-structured, and unstructured data sources.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] ETL tools can leverage object-oriented modeling and work with entities' representations persistently stored in a centrally located hub-and-spoke architecture.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Such a collection that contains representations of the entities or objects gathered from the data sources for ETL processing is called a metadata repository and it can reside in memory or be made persistent.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] By using a persistent metadata repository, ETL tools can transition from one-time projects to persistent middleware, performing data harmonization and data profiling consistently and in near-real time.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Extract, load, transform (ELT) is a variant of ETL where the extracted data is loaded into the target system first.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] The architecture for the analytics pipeline shall also consider where to cleanse and enrich data as well as how to conform dimensions.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Some of the benefits of an ELT process include speed and the ability to more easily handle both unstructured and structured data.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Ralph Kimball and Joe Caserta's book *The Data Warehouse ETL Toolkit*, (Wiley, 2004), which is used as a textbook for courses teaching ETL processes in data warehousing, addressed this issue.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Cloud-based data warehouses like Amazon Redshift, Google BigQuery, Microsoft Azure Synapse Analytics, and Snowflake provide highly scalable computing power.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] This lets businesses forgo preload transformations and replicate raw data into their data warehouses, where it can transform them as needed using SQL.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] After having used ELT, data may be processed further and stored in a data mart.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Most data integration tools skew towards ETL, while ELT is popular in database and data warehouse appliances.
[src:data-engineering/extract-transform-load] Similarly, it is possible to perform TEL (Transform, Extract, Load) where data is first transformed on a blockchain (as a way of recording changes to data, e.g., token burning) before extracting and loading into another data store.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] In computer science, **message queues** and **mailboxes** are software-engineering components typically used for inter-process communication (IPC), or for inter-thread communication within the same process.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] They use a queue for messaging – the passing of control or of content.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Group communication systems provide similar kinds of functionality.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] The message queue paradigm is a sibling of the publisher/subscriber pattern, and is typically one part of a larger message-oriented middleware system.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Most messaging systems support both the publisher/subscriber and message queue models in their API, e.g.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Competing Consumers pattern enables multiple concurrent consumers to process messages on the same message queue.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Message queues implement an asynchronous communication pattern between two or more processes/threads whereby the sending and receiving party do not need to interact with the message queue at the same time.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Messages placed onto the queue are stored until the recipient retrieves them.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Message queues have implicit or explicit limits on the size of data that may be transmitted in a single message and the number of messages that may remain outstanding on the queue.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Many implementations of message queues function internally within an operating system or within an application.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Such queues exist for the purposes of that system only.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Other implementations allow the passing of messages between different computer systems, potentially connecting multiple applications and multiple operating systems.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] These message queuing systems typically provide resilience functionality to ensure that messages do not get "lost" in the event of a system failure.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Examples of commercial implementations of this kind of message queuing software (also known as message-oriented middleware) include IBM MQ (formerly MQ Series) and Oracle Advanced Queuing (AQ).
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] There is a Java standard called Java Message Service, which has several proprietary and free software implementations.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Real-time operating systems (RTOSes) such as VxWorks and QNX encourage the use of message queuing as the primary inter-process or inter-thread communication mechanism.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] This can result in integration between message passing and CPU scheduling.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Early examples of commercial RTOSes that encouraged a message-queue basis to inter-thread communication also include VRTX and pSOS+, both of which date to the early 1980s.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] The Erlang programming language uses *processes* to provide concurrency; these processes communicate asynchronously using message queuing.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] The message queue software can be either proprietary, open source or a mix of both.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] It is then run either on premise in private servers or on external cloud servers (message queuing service).
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Examples on hardware-based messaging middleware vendors are Solace, Apigee, and IBM MQ.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] In a typical message-queueing implementation, a system administrator installs and configures message-queueing software (a queue manager or broker), and defines a named message queue.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Or they register with a message queuing service.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] An application then registers a software routine that "listens" for messages placed onto the queue.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Second and subsequent applications may connect to the queue and transfer a message onto it.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] The queue-manager software stores the messages until a receiving application connects and then calls the registered software routine.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] The receiving application then processes the message in an appropriate manner.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] These are all considerations that can have substantial effects on transaction semantics, system reliability, and system efficiency.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Historically, message queuing has used proprietary, closed protocols, restricting the ability for different operating systems or programming languages to interact in a heterogeneous set of environments.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] An early attempt to make message queuing more ubiquitous was Sun Microsystems' JMS specification, which provided a Java-only abstraction of a client API.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] This allowed Java developers to switch between providers of message queuing in a fashion similar to that of developers using SQL databases.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] In practice, given the diversity of message queuing techniques and scenarios, this wasn't always as practical as it could be.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] These protocols are at different stages of standardization and adoption.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] The first two operate at the same level as HTTP, MQTT at the level of TCP/IP.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Some proprietary implementations also use HTTP to provide message queuing by some implementations, such as Amazon's SQS.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] This is because it is always possible to layer asynchronous behaviour (which is what is required for message queuing) over a synchronous protocol using request-response semantics.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] However, such implementations are constrained by the underlying protocol in this case and may not be able to offer the full fidelity or set of options required in message passing above.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Many of the more widely known communications protocols in use operate synchronously.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] The HTTP protocol – used in the World Wide Web and in web services – offers an obvious example where a user sends a request for a web page and then waits for a reply.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] However, scenarios exist in which synchronous behaviour is not appropriate.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] For example, AJAX (Asynchronous JavaScript and XML) can be used to asynchronously send text, JSON or XML messages to update part of a web page with more relevant information.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Google uses this approach for their Google Suggest, a search feature which sends the user's partially typed queries to Google's servers and returns a list of possible full queries the user might be interested in the process of typing.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] This list is asynchronously updated as the user types.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Other asynchronous examples exist in event notification systems and publish/subscribe systems.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] In both of the above examples it would not make sense for the sender of the information to have to wait if, for example, one of the recipients had crashed.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Applications need not be exclusively synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] In all these sorts of situations, having a subsystem which performs message-queuing (or alternatively, a broadcast messaging system) can help improve the behavior of the overall system.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] There are two common message queue implementations in UNIX.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] One is part of the SYS V API, the other one is part of POSIX.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] UNIX SYS V implements message passing by keeping an array of linked lists as message queues.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Each message queue is identified by its index in the array, and has a unique descriptor.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] A given index can have multiple possible descriptors.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] UNIX gives standard functions to access the message passing feature.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] This system call takes a key as an argument and returns a descriptor of the queue with the matching key if it exists.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] flag is set, it makes a new message queue with the given key and returns its descriptor.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Used to receive a message from a given queue descriptor.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] The caller process must have read permissions for the queue.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Used to change message queue parameters like the owner.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] A message queue can be deleted only by its creator, owner, or the superuser.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] The POSIX.1-2001 message queue API is the later of the two UNIX message queue APIs.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] It is distinct from the SYS V API, but provides similar function.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] The unix man page `mq_overview(7)` provides an overview of POSIX message queues.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] Graphical user interfaces (GUIs) employ a message queue, also called an *event queue* or *input queue*, to pass graphical input actions, such as mouse clicks, keyboard events, or other user inputs, to the application program.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] The windowing system places messages indicating user or other events, such as timer ticks or messages sent by other threads, into the message queue.
[src:data-engineering/message-queue] The GUI application removes these events one at a time by calling a routine called `getNextEvent()` or similar in an event loop, and then calling the appropriate application routine to process that event.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] In computing, **online analytical processing (OLAP)** (/ˈoʊlæp/), is an approach to quickly answer multi-dimensional analytical (MDA) queries.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] The term *OLAP* was created as a slight modification of the traditional database term online transaction processing (OLTP).
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] OLAP is part of the broader category of business intelligence, which also encompasses relational databases, report writing and data mining.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Typical applications of OLAP include business reporting for sales, marketing, management reporting, business process management (BPM), budgeting and forecasting, financial reporting and similar areas, with new applications emerging, such as agriculture.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] OLAP tools enable users to analyse multidimensional data interactively from multiple perspectives.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] OLAP consists of three basic analytical operations: consolidation (roll-up), drill-down, and slicing and dicing.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Consolidation involves the aggregation of data that can be accumulated and computed in one or more dimensions.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] For example, all sales offices are rolled up to the sales department or sales division to anticipate sales trends.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] By contrast, the drill-down is a technique that allows users to navigate through the details.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] For instance, users can view the sales by individual products that make up a region's sales.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Slicing and dicing is a feature whereby users can take out (slicing) a specific set of data of the OLAP cube and view (dicing) the slices from different viewpoints.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] These viewpoints are sometimes called dimensions (such as looking at the same sales by salesperson, or by date, or by customer, or by product, or by region, etc.).
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Databases configured for OLAP use a multidimensional data model, allowing for complex analytical and ad hoc queries with a rapid execution time.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] They borrow aspects of navigational databases, hierarchical databases and relational databases.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] OLAP is typically contrasted to OLTP (online transaction processing), which is generally characterized by much less complex queries, in a larger volume, to process transactions rather than for the purpose of business intelligence or reporting.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Whereas OLAP systems are mostly optimized for read, OLTP has to process all kinds of queries (read, insert, update and delete).
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] At the core of any OLAP system is an OLAP cube (also called a 'multidimensional cube' or a hypercube).
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] It consists of numeric facts called *measures* that are categorized by *dimensions*.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] The measures are placed at the intersections of the hypercube, which is spanned by the dimensions as a vector space.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] The usual interface to manipulate an OLAP cube is a matrix interface, like Pivot tables in a spreadsheet program, which performs projection operations along the dimensions, such as aggregation or averaging.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] The cube metadata is typically created from a star schema or snowflake schema or fact constellation of tables in a relational database.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Measures are derived from the records in the fact table and dimensions are derived from the dimension tables.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Each *measure* can be thought of as having a set of *labels*, or meta-data associated with it.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] A *dimension* is what describes these *labels*; it provides information about the *measure*.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] A simple example would be a cube that contains a store's sales as a *measure*, and Date/Time as a *dimension*.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Each Sale has a Date/Time *label* that describes more about that sale.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Multidimensional structure is defined as "a variation of the relational model that uses multidimensional structures to organize data and express the relationships between data".
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] The structure is broken into cubes and the cubes are able to store and access data within the confines of each cube.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] "Each cell within a multidimensional structure contains aggregated data related to elements along each of its dimensions".
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Even when data is manipulated it remains easy to access and continues to constitute a compact database format.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Multidimensional structure is quite popular for analytical databases that use online analytical processing (OLAP) applications.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Analytical databases use these databases because of their ability to deliver answers to complex business queries swiftly.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Data can be viewed from different angles, which gives a broader perspective of a problem unlike other models.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] It has been claimed that for complex queries OLAP cubes can produce an answer in around 0.1% of the time required for the same query on OLTP relational data.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] The most important mechanism in OLAP which allows it to achieve such performance is the use of *aggregations*.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Aggregations are built from the fact table by changing the granularity on specific dimensions and aggregating up data along these dimensions, using an aggregate function (or *aggregation function*).
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] The number of possible aggregations is determined by every possible combination of dimension granularities.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] The combination of all possible aggregations and the base data contains the answers to every query which can be answered from the data.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Because usually there are many aggregations that can be calculated, often only a predetermined number are fully calculated; the remainder are solved on demand.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] The problem of deciding which aggregations (views) to calculate is known as the view selection problem.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] View selection can be constrained by the total size of the selected set of aggregations, the time to update them from changes in the base data, or both.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] The objective of view selection is typically to minimize the average time to answer OLAP queries, although some studies also minimize the update time.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Many approaches to the problem have been explored, including greedy algorithms, randomized search, genetic algorithms and A* search algorithm.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Some aggregation functions can be computed for the entire OLAP cube by precomputing values for each cell, and then computing the aggregation for a roll-up of cells by aggregating these aggregates, applying a divide and conquer algorithm to the multidimensional problem to compute them efficiently.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] For example, the overall sum of a roll-up is just the sum of the sub-sums in each cell.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Functions that can be decomposed in this way are called decomposable aggregation functions, and include `COUNT`, `MAX`, `MIN`, and `SUM`, which can be computed for each cell and then directly aggregated; these are known as self-decomposable aggregation functions.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] In other cases, the aggregate function cannot be computed without analyzing the entire set at once, though in some cases approximations can be computed; examples include `DISTINCT COUNT`, `MEDIAN`, and `MODE`; for example, the median of a set is not the median of medians of subsets.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] These latter are difficult to implement efficiently in OLAP, as they require computing the aggregate function on the base data, either computing them online (slow) or precomputing them for possible rollouts (large space).
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] OLAP systems have been traditionally categorized using the following taxonomy.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP (multi-dimensional online analytical processing) is the classic form of OLAP and is sometimes referred to as just OLAP.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP stores this data in an optimized multi-dimensional array storage, rather than in a relational database.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Some MOLAP tools require the pre-computation and storage of derived data, such as consolidations – the operation known as processing.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Such MOLAP tools generally utilize a pre-calculated data set referred to as a data cube.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] The data cube contains all the possible answers to a given range of questions.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] As a result, they have a very fast response to queries.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] On the other hand, updating can take a long time depending on the degree of pre-computation.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Pre-computation can also lead to what is known as data explosion.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Other MOLAP tools, particularly those that implement the functional database model do not pre-compute derived data but make all calculations on demand other than those that were previously requested and stored in a cache.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Examples of commercial products that use MOLAP are Cognos Powerplay, Oracle Database OLAP Option, MicroStrategy, Microsoft Analysis Services, Essbase, TM1, Jedox, and icCube.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] While ROLAP uses a relational database source, generally the database must be carefully designed for ROLAP use.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] A database which was designed for OLTP will not function well as a ROLAP database.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Therefore, ROLAP still involves creating an additional copy of the data.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] However, since it is a database, a variety of technologies can be used to populate the database.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] In the OLAP industry ROLAP is usually perceived as being able to scale for large data volumes but suffering from slower query performance as opposed to MOLAP.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] The OLAP Survey, the largest independent survey across all major OLAP products, being conducted for 6 years (2001 to 2006) have consistently found that companies using ROLAP report slower performance than those using MOLAP even when data volumes were taken into consideration.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] However, as with any survey there are a number of subtle issues that must be taken into account when interpreting the results.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Some companies select ROLAP because they intend to re-use existing relational database tables—these tables will frequently not be optimally designed for OLAP use.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] The superior flexibility of ROLAP tools allows this less-than-optimal design to work, but performance suffers.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP tools in contrast would force the data to be re-loaded into an optimal OLAP design.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] The undesirable trade-off between additional ETL cost and slow query performance has ensured that most commercial OLAP tools now use a "Hybrid OLAP" (HOLAP) approach, which allows the model designer to decide which portion of the data will be stored in MOLAP and which portion in ROLAP.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] There is no clear agreement across the industry as to what constitutes "Hybrid OLAP", except that a database will divide data between relational and specialized storage.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] For example, for some vendors, a HOLAP database will use relational tables to hold the larger quantities of detailed data and use specialized storage for at least some aspects of the smaller quantities of more-aggregate or less-detailed data.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] HOLAP addresses the shortcomings of MOLAP and ROLAP by combining the capabilities of both approaches.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] HOLAP tools can utilize both pre-calculated cubes and relational data sources.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] In this mode HOLAP stores *aggregations* in MOLAP for fast query performance, and detailed data in ROLAP to optimize time of cube *processing*.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] In this mode HOLAP stores some slice of data, usually the more recent one (i.e. sliced by Time dimension) in MOLAP for fast query performance, and older data in ROLAP.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Moreover, we can store some dices in MOLAP and others in ROLAP, leveraging the fact that in a large cuboid, there will be dense and sparse subregions.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] The first product to provide HOLAP storage was Holos, but the technology also became available in other commercial products such as Microsoft Analysis Services, Oracle Database OLAP Option, MicroStrategy and SAP AG BI Accelerator.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] The hybrid OLAP approach combines ROLAP and MOLAP technology, benefiting from the greater scalability of ROLAP and the faster computation of MOLAP.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] For example, a HOLAP server may store large volumes of detailed data in a relational database, while aggregations are kept in a separate MOLAP store.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Each type has certain benefits, although there is disagreement about the specifics of the benefits between providers.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Unlike relational databases, which had SQL as the standard query language, and widespread APIs such as ODBC, JDBC and OLEDB, there was no such unification in the OLAP world for a long time.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] The first real standard API was OLE DB for OLAP specification from Microsoft which appeared in 1997 and introduced the MDX query language.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Several OLAP vendors – both server and client – adopted it.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] In 2001 Microsoft and Hyperion announced the XML for Analysis specification, which was endorsed by most of the OLAP vendors.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Since this also used MDX as a query language, MDX became the de facto standard.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Since September-2011 LINQ can be used to query SSAS OLAP cubes from Microsoft .NET.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] The first product that performed OLAP queries was *Express,* which was released in 1970 (and acquired by Oracle in 1995 from Information Resources).
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] However, the term did not appear until 1993 when it was coined by Edgar F.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Codd, who has been described as "the father of the relational database".
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Codd's paper resulted from a short consulting assignment which Codd undertook for former Arbor Software (later Hyperion Solutions, and in 2007 acquired by Oracle), as a sort of marketing coup.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] The company had released its own OLAP product, *Essbase*, a year earlier.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] As a result, Codd's "twelve laws of online analytical processing" were explicit in their reference to Essbase.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] There was some ensuing controversy and when Computerworld learned that Codd was paid by Arbor, it retracted the article.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] The OLAP market experienced strong growth in the late 1990s with dozens of commercial products going into market.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] In 1998, Microsoft released its first OLAP Server – Microsoft Analysis Services, which drove wide adoption of OLAP technology and moved it into the mainstream.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] OLAP clients include many spreadsheet programs like Excel, web application, SQL, dashboard tools, etc.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Many clients support interactive data exploration where users select dimensions and measures of interest.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Some dimensions are used as filters (for slicing and dicing the data) while others are selected as the axes of a pivot table or pivot chart.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Users can also vary aggregation level (for drilling-down or rolling-up) the displayed view.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Clients can also offer a variety of graphical widgets such as sliders, geographic maps, heat maps and more which can be grouped and coordinated as dashboards.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] An extensive list of clients appears in the visualization column of the comparison of OLAP servers table.
[src:data-engineering/online-analytical-processing] Below is a list of top OLAP vendors in 2006, with figures in millions of US Dollars.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] The term *transaction* can have two different meanings, both of which may apply.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] In the context of computers or database transactions, it denotes an atomic change of state, whereas in business or finance, it typically refers to an exchange of economic entities, as used by the Transaction Processing Performance Council or commercial transactions.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] OLTP systems may use transactions of the first type to record transactions of the second type.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] OLTP is typically contrasted with online analytical processing (OLAP), which is generally characterized by much more complex queries and is executed in smaller volumes, for the purpose of business intelligence or reporting rather than processing transactions.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] Whereas OLTP systems handle all kinds of queries (read, insert, update, and delete), OLAP is generally optimized for read-only operations and may not support other types of queries.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] OLTP also operates differently from batch processing and grid computing.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] In addition, OLTP is often contrasted with online event processing (OLEP), which is based on distributed event logs to provide strong consistency in large-scale heterogeneous systems.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] While OLTP is associated with short atomic transactions, OLEP allows for more flexible distribution patterns and higher scalability, but with increased latency and without guaranteed upper bound on processing time.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] OLTP has also been used to refer to processing in which the system responds immediately to user requests.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] An automated teller machine (ATM) is an example of a commercial transaction-processing application.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] Online transaction processing applications typically have high throughput and are insert- or update-intensive in database management.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] These applications are used concurrently by hundreds of users.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] The key goals of OLTP applications are availability, speed, concurrency, and recoverability (durability).
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] Reduced paper trails and the faster, more accurate forecasting of revenues and expenses are examples of how OLTP simplifies business operations.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] However, like many modern online information technology solutions, some systems require offline maintenance, which can affect the cost-benefit analysis of an online transaction processing system.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] An OLTP system is an accessible data processing system in modern enterprises.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] Examples of OLTP systems include order entry, retail sales, and financial transaction systems.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] Online transaction processing systems increasingly require support for transactions that span a network and may involve more than one company.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] For this reason, modern OLTP software often employs client- or server-processing and brokering software, allowing transactions to run on different computer platforms within a network.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] In large applications, efficient OLTP may rely on sophisticated transaction management software (such as IBM CICS) and database optimization techniques to facilitate the processing of large numbers of concurrent updates to an OLTP-oriented database.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] For more demanding decentralized database systems, OLTP brokering programs can distribute transaction processing among multiple computers on a network.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] OLTP is often integrated into service-oriented architecture (SOA) and web services.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] OLTP involves gathering input data, processing it, and updating existing data to reflect the collected and processed information.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] Most organizations use a database management system to support OLTP.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] OLTP typically operates in a client-server system.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] Online transaction processing is concerned with concurrency and atomicity.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] Concurrency control ensures that two users accessing the same data in a database system cannot modify it simultaneously; one user must wait until the other has finished processing before making changes.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] Atomicity ensures that all steps in a transaction are completed successfully as a group; if any step fails, all other steps must also fail.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] To build an OLTP system, a designer must know that a large number of concurrent users does not interfere with the system performance.
[src:data-engineering/online-transaction-processing] To improve the performance of an OLTP system, a designer should avoid excessive use of indexes and clusters.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] In computing, the **star schema** or **star model** is the simplest style of data mart schema and is the approach most widely used to develop data warehouses and dimensional data marts.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] The star schema consists of one or more fact tables referencing any number of dimension tables.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] The star schema is an important special case of the snowflake schema, and is more effective for handling simpler queries.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] The star schema gets its name from the physical model's resemblance to a star shape with a fact table at its center and the dimension tables surrounding it representing the star's points.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] The star schema separates business process data into facts, which hold the measurable, quantitative data about a business, and dimensions which are descriptive attributes related to fact data.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] Examples of fact data include sales price, sale quantity, time, distance, speed and weight measurements.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] Related dimension attribute examples include product models, product colors, product sizes, geographic locations, and salesperson names.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] A star schema that has many dimensions is sometimes called a *centipede schema*.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] Having dimensions of only a few attributes, while simpler to maintain, results in queries with many table joins and makes the star schema less easy to use.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] Fact tables record measurements or metrics for a specific event.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] Fact tables generally consist of numeric values, and foreign keys to dimensional data where descriptive information is kept.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] Fact tables are designed to a low level of uniform detail (referred to as "granularity" or "grain"), meaning facts can record events at a very atomic level.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] This can result in the accumulation of a large number of records in a fact table over time.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] Fact tables are generally assigned a surrogate key to ensure each row can be uniquely identified.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] Dimension tables usually have a relatively small number of records compared to fact tables, but each record may have a very large number of attributes to describe the fact data.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] Dimension tables are generally assigned a surrogate primary key, usually a single-column integer data type, mapped to the combination of dimension attributes that form the natural key.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] Star schemas are denormalized, meaning the typical rules of normalization applied to transactional relational databases are relaxed during star-schema design and implementation.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] A star schema denormalizes dimension attributes into single wide tables to improve understandability and reduce join complexity for analytic workloads.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] By contrast, a **snowflake schema** normalizes dimension hierarchies into multiple linked tables.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] Kimball recommends avoiding snowflaking unless there is a clear need (for example, extremely large dimensions) because it adds complexity for users and can hurt query performance.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] Star schemas align well with multidimensional/OLAP models commonly used in decision support.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] Dimensional modeling distinguishes a central **fact table** and surrounding **dimension tables**.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] Common fact table types in star schemas are **transaction**, **periodic snapshot**, and **accumulating snapshot**; frequently used conformed dimensions include date/time, product, customer, organization, and geography.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] Analytic queries over a star schema usually join one large fact table with a handful of relatively small dimensions; many DBMSs implement ‘‘star-join’’ optimizations for this pattern.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] Performance characteristics of such workloads are commonly studied using the **Star Schema Benchmark (SSB)**.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] Consider a database of sales, perhaps from a store chain, classified by date, store and product.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] The image of the schema to the right is a star schema version of the sample schema provided in the snowflake schema article.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] `Fact_Sales` is the fact table and there are three dimension tables `Dim_Date`, `Dim_Store` and `Dim_Product`.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] Each dimension table has a primary key on its `Id` column, relating to one of the columns (viewed as rows in the example schema) of the `Fact_Sales` table's three-column (compound) primary key (`Date_Id`, `Store_Id`, `Product_Id`).
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] The non-primary key `Units_Sold` column of the fact table in this example represents a measure or metric that can be used in calculations and analysis.
[src:data-engineering/star-schema] The non-primary key columns of the dimension tables represent additional attributes of the dimensions (such as the `Year` of the `Dim_Date` dimension).
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] In computer science, **stream processing** (also known as **event stream processing**, **data stream processing**, or **distributed stream processing**) is a programming paradigm which views streams, or sequences of events in time, as the central input and output objects of computation.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Stream processing encompasses dataflow programming, reactive programming, and distributed data processing.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Stream processing systems use streaming algorithms to trace parallel processing for data streams.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] The stream processing paradigm simplifies parallel software and hardware by restricting the parallel computation that can be performed.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Given a sequence of data (a *stream*), a series of operations (*kernel functions*) is applied to each element in the stream.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Kernel functions are usually pipelined, and optimal local on-chip memory reuse is attempted, in order to minimize the loss in bandwidth, associated with external memory interaction.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] *Uniform streaming*, where one kernel function is applied to all elements in the stream, is typical.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Since the kernel and stream abstractions expose data dependencies, compiler tools can fully automate and optimize on-chip management tasks.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Stream processing hardware can use scoreboarding, for example, to initiate a direct memory access (DMA) when dependencies become known.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] The elimination of manual DMA management reduces software complexity, and an associated elimination for hardware cached I/O, reduces the data area expanse that has to be involved with service by specialized computational units such as arithmetic logic units.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] During the 1980s stream processing was explored within dataflow programming.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] An example is the language SISAL (Streams and Iteration in a Single Assignment Language).
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Stream processing is essentially a compromise, driven by a data-centric model that works very well for traditional DSP or GPU-type applications (such as image, video and digital signal processing) but less so for general purpose processing with more randomized data access (such as databases).
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] By sacrificing some flexibility in the model, the implications allow easier, faster and more efficient execution.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Depending on the context, processor design may be tuned for maximum efficiency or a trade-off for flexibility.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] For each record we can only read from the input, perform operations on it, and write to the output.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] It is permissible to have multiple inputs and multiple outputs, but never a piece of memory that is both readable and writable.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] By way of illustration, the following code fragments demonstrate detection of patterns within event streams.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] The first is an example of processing a data stream using a continuous SQL query (a query that executes forever processing arriving data based on timestamps and window duration).
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] This code fragment illustrates a JOIN of two data streams, one for stock orders, and one for the resulting stock trades.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] The query outputs a stream of all Orders matched by a Trade within one second of the Order being placed.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] The output stream is sorted by timestamp, in this case, the timestamp from the Orders stream.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Another sample code fragment detects weddings among a flow of external "events" such as church bells ringing, the appearance of a man in a tuxedo or morning suit, a woman in a flowing white gown and rice flying through the air.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] A "complex" or "composite" event is what one infers from the individual simple events: a wedding is happening.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Basic computers started from a sequential execution paradigm.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Traditional CPUs are SISD based, which means they conceptually perform only one operation at a time.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] As the computing needs of the world evolved, the amount of data to be managed increased very quickly.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] It was obvious that the sequential programming model could not cope with the increased need for processing power.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Various efforts have been spent on finding alternative ways to perform massive amounts of computations but the only solution was to exploit some level of parallel execution.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] The result of those efforts was SIMD, a programming paradigm which allowed applying one instruction to multiple instances of (different) data.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Most of the time, SIMD was being used in a SWAR environment.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] By using more complicated structures, one could also have MIMD parallelism.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Although those two paradigms were efficient, real-world implementations were plagued with limitations from memory alignment problems to synchronization issues and limited parallelism.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Only few SIMD processors survived as stand-alone components; most were embedded in standard CPUs.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Consider a simple program adding up two arrays containing 100 4-component vectors (i.e.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] This is the sequential paradigm that is most familiar.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Variations do exist (such as inner loops, structures and such), but they ultimately boil down to that construct.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] It assumes the instruction `vector_sum` works.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Although this is what happens with instruction intrinsics, much information is actually not taken into account here such as the number of vector components and their data format.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] You can see however, this method reduces the number of decoded instructions from *numElements * componentsPerElement* to *numElements*.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] The number of jump instructions is also decreased, as the loop is run fewer times.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] These gains result from the parallel execution of the four mathematical operations.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] What happened however is that the packed SIMD register holds a certain amount of data so it's not possible to get more parallelism.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] The speed up is somewhat limited by the assumption we made of performing four parallel operations (please note this is common for both AltiVec and SSE).
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] In this paradigm, the whole dataset is defined, rather than each component block being defined separately.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Describing the set of data is assumed to be in the first two rows.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] After that, the result is inferred from the sources and kernel.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] For simplicity, there's a 1:1 mapping between input and output data but this does not need to be.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Applied kernels can also be much more complex.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] An implementation of this paradigm can "unroll" a loop internally.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] This allows throughput to scale with chip complexity, easily utilizing hundreds of ALUs.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] The elimination of complex data patterns makes much of this extra power available.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] While stream processing is a branch of SIMD/MIMD processing, they must not be confused.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Although SIMD implementations can often work in a "streaming" manner, their performance is not comparable: the model envisions a very different usage pattern which allows far greater performance by itself.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] It has been noted that when applied on generic processors such as standard CPU, only a 1.5x speedup can be reached.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] By contrast, ad-hoc stream processors easily reach over 10x performance, mainly attributed to the more efficient memory access and higher levels of parallel processing.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Although there are various degrees of flexibility allowed by the model, stream processors usually impose some limitations on the kernel or stream size.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] For example, consumer hardware often lacks the ability to perform high-precision math, lacks complex indirection chains or presents lower limits on the number of instructions which can be executed.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Stanford University stream processing projects included the Stanford Real-Time Programmable Shading Project started in 1999.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] A prototype called Imagine was developed in 2002.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] A project called Merrimac ran until about 2004.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] AT&T also researched stream-enhanced processors as graphics processing units rapidly evolved in both speed and functionality.[1] Since these early days, dozens of stream processing languages have been developed, as well as specialized hardware.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] The most immediate challenge in the realm of parallel processing does not lie as much in the type of hardware architecture used, but in how easy it will be to program the system in question in a real-world environment with acceptable performance.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Machines like Imagine use a straightforward single-threaded model with automated dependencies, memory allocation and DMA scheduling.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] This in itself is a result of the research at MIT and Stanford in finding an optimal *layering of tasks* between programmer, tools and hardware.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Programmers beat tools in mapping algorithms to parallel hardware, and tools beat programmers in figuring out smartest memory allocation schemes, etc.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Of particular concern are MIMD designs such as Cell, for which the programmer needs to deal with application partitioning across multiple cores and deal with process synchronization and load balancing.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] A drawback of SIMD programming was the issue of array-of-structures (AoS) and structure-of-arrays (SoA).
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] When multiple of these structures exist in memory they are placed end to end creating an arrays in an *array of structures* (AoS) topology.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] This means that should some algorithm be applied to the location of each particle in turn it must skip over memory locations containing the other attributes.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] If these attributes are not needed this results in wasteful usage of the CPU cache.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Additionally, a SIMD instruction will typically expect the data it will operate on to be contiguous in memory, the elements may also need to be aligned.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] By moving the memory location of the data out of the structure data can be better organised for efficient access in a stream and for SIMD instructions to operate one.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] A *structure of arrays* (SoA), as shown below, can allow this.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Instead of holding the data in the structure, it holds only pointers (memory locations) for the data.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Shortcomings are that if multiple attributes to of an object are to be operated on they might now be distant in memory and so result in a cache miss.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] The aligning and any needed padding lead to increased memory usage.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Overall, memory management may be more complicated if structures are added and removed for example.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] For stream processors, the usage of structures is encouraged.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] From an application point of view, all the attributes can be defined with some flexibility.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Taking GPUs as reference, there is a set of attributes (at least 16) available.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] For each attribute, the application can state the number of components and the format of the components (but only primitive data types are supported for now).
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] The various attributes are then attached to a memory block, possibly defining a *stride* between 'consecutive' elements of the same attributes, effectively allowing interleaved data.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] When the GPU begins the stream processing, it will *gather* all the various attributes in a single set of parameters (usually this looks like a structure or a "magic global variable"), performs the operations and *scatters* the results to some memory area for later processing (or retrieving).
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] More modern stream processing frameworks provide a FIFO like interface to structure data as a literal stream.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] This abstraction provides a means to specify data dependencies implicitly while enabling the runtime/hardware to take full advantage of that knowledge for efficient computation.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] One of the simplest and most efficient stream processing modalities to date for C++, is RaftLib, which enables linking independent compute kernels together as a data flow graph using C++ stream operators.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Apart from specifying streaming applications in high-level languages, models of computation (MoCs) also have been widely used as dataflow models and process-based models.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Historically, CPUs began implementing various tiers of memory access optimizations because of the ever-increasing performance when compared to relatively slow growing external memory bandwidth.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] As this gap widened, big amounts of die area were dedicated to hiding memory latencies.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Since fetching information and opcodes to those few ALUs is expensive, very little die area is dedicated to actual mathematical machinery (as a rough estimation, consider it to be less than 10%).
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] A similar architecture exists on stream processors but thanks to the new programming model, the amount of transistors dedicated to management is actually very little.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Beginning from a whole system point of view, stream processors usually exist in a controlled environment.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] GPUs do exist on an add-in board (this seems to also apply to Imagine).
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] CPUs continue do the job of managing system resources, running applications, and such.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] The stream processor is usually equipped with a fast, efficient, proprietary memory bus (crossbar switches are now common, multi-buses have been employed in the past).
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] The exact amount of memory lanes is dependent on the market range.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] As this is written, there are still 64-bit wide interconnections around (entry-level).
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Most mid-range models use a fast 128-bit crossbar switch matrix (4 or 2 segments), while high-end models deploy huge amounts of memory (actually up to 512 MB) with a slightly slower crossbar that is 256 bits wide.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] By contrast, standard processors from Intel Pentium to some Athlon 64 have only a single 64-bit wide data bus.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Memory access patterns are much more predictable.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] While arrays do exist, their dimension is fixed at kernel invocation.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] The thing which most closely matches a multiple pointer indirection is an *indirection chain*, which is however guaranteed to finally read or write from a specific memory area (inside a stream).
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Because of the SIMD nature of the stream processor's execution units (ALUs clusters), read/write operations are expected to happen in bulk, so memories are optimized for high bandwidth rather than low latency (this is a difference from Rambus and DDR SDRAM, for example).
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] This also allows for efficient memory bus negotiations.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Most (90%) of a stream processor's work is done on-chip, requiring only 1% of the global data to be stored to memory.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] This is where knowing the kernel temporaries and dependencies pays.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Internally, a stream processor features some clever communication and management circuits but what's interesting is the *Stream Register File* (SRF).
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] This is conceptually a large cache in which stream data is stored to be transferred to external memory in bulks.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] As a cache-like software-controlled structure to the various ALUs, the SRF is shared between all the various ALU clusters.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] The key concept and innovation here done with Stanford's Imagine chip is that the compiler is able to automate and allocate memory in an optimal way, fully transparent to the programmer.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] The dependencies between kernel functions and data is known through the programming model which enables the compiler to perform flow analysis and optimally pack the SRFs.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Commonly, this cache and DMA management can take up the majority of a project's schedule, something the stream processor (or at least Imagine) totally automates.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Tests done at Stanford showed that the compiler did an as well or better job at scheduling memory than if you hand tuned the thing with much effort.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] There is proof; there can be a lot of clusters because inter-cluster communication is assumed to be rare.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Internally however, each cluster can efficiently exploit a much lower amount of ALUs because intra-cluster communication is common and thus needs to be highly efficient.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] To keep those ALUs fetched with data, each ALU is equipped with local register files (LRFs), which are basically its usable registers.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] This three-tiered data access pattern, makes it easy to keep temporary data away from slow memories, thus making the silicon implementation highly efficient and power-saving.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Although an order of magnitude speedup can be reasonably expected (even from mainstream GPUs when computing in a streaming manner), not all applications benefit from this.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Communication latencies are actually the biggest problem.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Although PCI Express improved this with full-duplex communications, getting a GPU (and possibly a generic stream processor) to work will possibly take long amounts of time.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] This means it's usually counter-productive to use them for small datasets.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Because changing the kernel is a rather expensive operation the stream architecture also incurs penalties for small streams, a behaviour referred to as the *short stream effect*.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Pipelining is a very widespread and heavily used practice on stream processors, with GPUs featuring pipelines exceeding 200 stages.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] The cost for switching settings is dependent on the setting being modified but it is now considered to always be expensive.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] To avoid those problems at various levels of the pipeline, many techniques have been deployed such as "über shaders" and "texture atlases".
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Those techniques are game-oriented because of the nature of GPUs, but the concepts are interesting for generic stream processing as well.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Most programming languages for stream processors start with Java, C or C++ and add extensions which provide specific instructions to allow application developers to tag kernels and/or streams.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] This also applies to most shading languages, which can be considered stream programming languages to a certain degree.
[src:data-engineering/stream-processing] Commercial implementations are either general purpose or tied to specific hardware by a vendor.
